{
  format: 1
  name: decimal-numeric-equality-tiebroken-by-identity
  suite: scenario
  spec: ["#annex-b", "§B.1", "§B.5"]
  tags: ["ordering"]
  note: '''
    §B.1 decimal: "mathematical decimal order; numerically equal canonical
    values compare equal". Two attacks:
      - Scale-as-value: "1.0" and "1.00" are numerically equal, so they compare
        EQUAL for sorting; an implementation that ordered by scale or by text
        would separate them. Being equal on the sort key, they fall to the
        final row-identity tiebreaker (§B.5), which is key ascending: key
        "k_a" precedes key "k_b".
      - Magnitude vs text: "2" < "10" numerically, but a text sorter gives
        "10" < "2". The value order must be numeric.
    The view projects only `id`, so the case never asserts a canonical
    trailing-zero spelling of decimal (Annex A does not pin that spelling for
    this corpus). It asserts only ROW ORDER, which the two rules above fully
    determine. decimal values are authored as strings per the corpus
    convention.
  '''

  package: {
    $liasse: 1
    $app: "t.annexb.decimal@1.0.0"
    $model: {
      rows: {
        $key: "id"
        id: "text"
        v: "decimal"
      }
      $public: {
        by_v: { $view: ".rows { id, $sort: [v, id] }" }
      }
    }
    $data: {
      rows: {
        k_d: { v: "10" }
        k_b: { v: "1.0" }
        k_c: { v: "2" }
        k_a: { v: "1.00" }
      }
    }
  }

  steps: [
    { watch: "public.by_v", id: "w1",
      expect_init: { value: [
        { id: "k_a" }
        { id: "k_b" }
        { id: "k_c" }
        { id: "k_d" }
      ] } }
  ]
}
